body:
This is a second look at the problem in #3365 and proposing a simple fix for it.

To summarize: in .NET Core 3.1, `Enumerable.Empty<T>` returns an `System.Linq.EmptyPartition<T>` which does not implement `ICollection<T>`. Since existing values for enumerable destinations are cast to `ICollection<T>`, an exception is thrown.

If we change the generated expression tree to not do a hard cast (`(T)value` represented by `Expression.Convert`) on the destination, but instead do `value as T`, represented by `Expression.TypeAs`, the destination will have a value of `null` if it's not assignable to `ICollection<T>`. From there we'll take the same code-path as if we didn't initialize the property at all, which means initializing it with a new list and then adding the values.

You can see the change in context here: https://github.com/wagich/AutoMapper/commit/b6b24b554eda014baff3a22894d6dd8c6a73e065. I'd be happy to create a PRâ€¦

### Source/destination types

```csharp
public class Source
{
    public int[] Values { get; set; } = Array.Empty<int>();
}

public class Destination
{
    public IEnumerable<int> Values { get; set; } = Enumerable.Empty<int>();
}
```

### Mapping configuration

```csharp
CreateMap<Source, Destination>();
```

### Version: 10.1.1

### Expected behavior

Mapping to a property that was initialized to `Enumerable.Empty<T>()` in .NET Core 3.1 should work.

### Actual behavior

Throws an `InvalidCastException`:
Unable to cast object of type 'System.Linq.EmptyPartition\`1[System.Int32]' to type 'System.Collections.Generic.ICollection\`1[System.Int32]'.

### Steps to reproduce

```csharp
var config = new MapperConfiguration(config =>
{
    config.CreateMap<Source, Destination>();
});
var mapper = config.CreateMapper();

var src = new Source
{
    Values = new[] { 1, 2 }
};
var existingDest = new Destination();
existingDest = mapper.Map(src, existingDest);
```
